related_questions.question: Which is better for skin, cocoa butter or shea butter?
related_questions.snippet: Cocoa butter is slightly thicker than shea butter so it may clog your pores. Although shea butter is rich and luxurious, it is actually lightweight on your skin! If your skin is extra dry, try a deep conditioning shea butter to nourish your skin and improve common dry spots like your knees and elbows.

related_questions.question: Does cocoa butter contain dairy?
related_questions.snippet: Cocoa butter is naturally free of dairy, eggs, honey, and other animal-derived ingredients, making it suitable for vegans. However, many products made with cocoa butter aren't vegan, so it's best to check a food's nutrition label before eating it.

related_questions.snippet: Cocoa butter is safe for use on the skin and generally doesn't cause irritation.

related_questions.question: What is cocoa butter good for?
related_questions.snippet: Cocoa Butter Benefits Cocoa butter is a decent source of vitamin E, which benefits your body in many ways. Vitamin E supports vision, reproduction, and the health of your brain, skin, and blood. Cocoa butter contains a high amount of fatty acids, which make it well-suited as a main ingredient in skin cream.

buttons.subtitle: What Is Cocoa Butter?
buttons.title: Health Benefits of Cocoa Butter - WebMD
buttons.snippet: Cocoa butter, also called theobroma oil, is a light-yellow vegetable fat that comes from cocoa beans.
snippet_highlighted_words: a light-yellow vegetable fat that comes from cocoa beans

buttons.subtitle: What Does Cocoa Butter Do To Chocolate?
buttons.title: What Is Cocoa Butter? - The Spruce Eats
buttons.snippet: Cocoa butter is pale yellow and is sold in solid form; it needs to be melted before cooking. It is used to make white chocolate and other chocolate bars, giving the confection its smooth and silky mouthfeel. Because of its texture and long shelf life, cocoa butter is also used as an ingredient in skin-care products.
snippet_highlighted_words: giving the confection its smooth and silky mouthfeel

buttons.subtitle: Materials In Cocoa Butter
buttons.title: Cocoa Butter: Nutrition, Uses, Benefits, Downsides - Healthline
buttons.snippet: Cocoa butter consists of a combination of saturated and unsaturated fatty acids. It contains approximately 60% saturated fat (palmitic, stearic, lauric, and myristic acids), 35% monounsaturated fat (oleic acid), and 1% polyunsaturated fat (linoleic acid) ( 3 ).

buttons.subtitle: How To Use Cocoa Butter
buttons.title: What is Cacao Butter and How Do I Use It? - Navitas Organics
buttons.snippet: Use melted natural cacao butter in place of other kinds of oil, margarine or dairy butter in recipes like cookies, brownies and cakes for a subtle chocolate innuendo. For best results, use a partial substitute only, keeping in mind that cacao butter will continue to firm up the recipe a little after cooking.

buttons.subtitle: Cocoa Butter Effects
buttons.title: Cocoa Butter: Benefits, Uses, and More - Healthline
buttons.snippet: The fat in cocoa butter forms a protective barrier over skin to hold in moisture. Cocoa butter is also rich in natural plant compounds called phytochemicals. These substances may improve blood flow to the skin and slow skin aging by protecting against damage from the sun's harmful UV rays.
snippet_highlighted_words: improve blood flow to the skin and slow skin aging by protecting against damage from the sun's harmful UV rays

buttons.subtitle: How Do You Get Cocoa Butter
buttons.title: What is Cacao Butter - Honest to Goodness
buttons.snippet: To harness cacao butter, the beans are harvested from the cacao pods, and then cleaned and roasted. Next, the beans are stripped from their shells and crushed into nibs, which are then ground into a liquid known as cocoa liquor. This liquid is then pressed to separate the fat. This fat, friends, is cacao butter!
